<section xml:id="sect-gauss-quad-revisit">
  <title>Gaussian Quadrature: revisited</title>

  <p>
    As we saw before in Chapter 4, we wish to find an approximate value for
    <me>
      \begin{aligned}I\amp = \int_{a}^{b} f(x) \, dx\end{aligned}
    </me>
    typically, we let
    <me>
      \begin{aligned}I \approx I_{n}\amp = \sum_{k=1}^{n} w_{i} f(x_{i})\end{aligned}
    </me>
    where <m>w_{i}</m> are called the weights and <m>x_{i}</m> are the nodes.
    The technique of <alert>Gaussian Quadrature</alert> finds the weights and the nodes with highest degree of precision as possible, that is, it integrates polynomials of highest possible degree exactly.
  </p>

  <p>
    In the previous few sections, we have seen the Legendre Polynomials, which are the set of polynomials that are orthogonal with respect to the weight <m>w(x)\equiv 1</m>.
    The next theorem shows that if the nodes are the roots of the Legendre polynomials, then the result is that sought for Gaussian Quadrature.
  </p>

  <theorem>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Suppose the <m>x_{1}, x_{2}, \ldots, x_{n}</m> are the roots of <m>L_{n}(x)</m>, the <m>n</m>th degree Legendre Polynomial.
        In addition, let
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}c_{k}\amp = \int_{-1}^{1} \prod_{\stackrel{j=1}{j\neq k}}^{n} \frac{x-x_{j}}{x_{k}-x_{j}}\, dx.
          \label{eq:gq:weights}\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>P(x)</m> is any polynomial of degree less than <m>2n</m>, then
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}\int_{-1}^{1} P(x) \, dx\amp = \sum_{k=1}^{n} c_{k} P(x_{k}).\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
    </statement>


    <proof>
      <p>
        First, we will consider polynomials <m>P(x)</m> of degree less than <m>n</m> and write it as
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}P(x)\amp = \sum_{k=1}^{n} P(x_{i}) \prod_{\stackrel{j=1}{j\neq k}}^{n} \frac{x-x_{j}}{x_{k}-x_{j}}\end{aligned}
        </me>
        with <m>x_{k}</m> as the roots of <m>L_{n}(x)</m>.
        This is the Lagrange form of the polynomial and since they are unique...
      </p>

      <p>
        Integrating on <m>[-1,1]</m>,
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}\int_{-1}^{1} P(x) \, dx\amp = \int_{-1}^{1} \sum_{k=1}^{n} P(x_{k}) \prod{\stackrel{j=1}{j\neq k}}^{n} \frac{x-x_{j}}{x_{k}-x_{j}}\, dx \\\amp = \sum_{k=1}^{n} P(x_{k}) \int_{-1}^{1} \prod_{\stackrel{j=1}{j\neq k}}^{n} \frac{x-x_{j}}{x_{k}-x_{j}}\, dx \\\amp = \sum_{k=1}^{n} c_{k} P(x_{k})\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        If <m>P(x)</m> has degree at least <m>n</m> and at most <m>2n-1</m>, then we divide <m>P(x)</m> by <m>L_{n}(x)</m> to get
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}P(x)\amp = Q(x) L_{n}(x) + R(x)\end{aligned}
        </me>
        where <m>L_{n}(x)</m> is the <m>n</m>th degree Legendre polynomial.
        Note that at the Legendre roots,
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}P(x_{k})\amp = Q(x_{k}) L_{n}(x_{k}) +R(x_{k}) = Q(x_{k}) \cdot 0 + R(x_{k}) = R(x_{k}).\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Since the Legendre polynomials are orthogonal to polynomials of degree less than <m>n</m>, then
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}\int_{-1}^{1} Q(x) L_{n}(x) \, dx\amp = 0\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Also, since <m>R(x)</m> is a polynomial of degree less than <m>n</m>, therefore part 1 of the proof leads to
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}\int_{-1}^{1} R(x) \, dx\amp = \sum_{k=1}^{n} c_{k} R(x_{k})\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        Using these parts,
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}\int_{-1}^{1} P(x) \, dx\amp = \int_{-1}^{1} \bigl( Q(x) L_{n}(x) + R(x) \bigr) \, dx = \int_{-1}^{1} R(x) \,dx = \sum_{k=1}^{n} c_{k} R(x_{k}) = \sum_{k=1}^{n} c_{k} P(x_{k})\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
    </proof>
  </theorem>

  <p>
    The consequence of this theorem is that using the Legendre roots and the weights given (eq:gq:weights) that this is Gaussian Quadrature.
  </p>

  <p>
    <dl>
    <li>
      <title><m>n=2</m></title>

      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle L_{2}(x) = \frac{3}{2}x^{2} - \frac{1}{2}</m>. The roots are <m>\pm \sqrt{1/3}</m> and the weights are
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}c_{1}\amp = \int_{-1}^{1} \frac{x-\sqrt{1/3}}{-\sqrt{1/3}-\sqrt{1/3}}\,dx = 1 \\ c_{2}\amp = \int_{-1}^{1} \frac{x+\sqrt{1/3}}{\sqrt{1/3}+\sqrt{1/3}}\,dx = 1\end{aligned}
        </me>
        resulting in the Gaussian Quadrature formula,
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}\int_{-1}^{1} f(x) \, dx\amp \approx f\biggl(-\sqrt{\frac{1}{3}}\biggr)+ f\biggl(\sqrt{\frac{1}{3}}\biggr)\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <title><m>n=3</m></title>

      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle L_{3}(x) = \frac{5}{2}x^{3} - \frac{3}{2}x</m>. The roots are <m>0, \pm \sqrt{3/5}</m> and the weights are:
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}c_{1}\amp = \int_{-1}^{1} \frac{(x-0)(x-\sqrt{3/5})}{(-\sqrt{3/5}-0)(-\sqrt{3/5}-\sqrt{3/5})}\,dx = \frac{5}{9}\\ c_{2}\amp = \int_{-1}^{1} \frac{(x-\sqrt{3/5})(x+\sqrt{3/5})}{(0-\sqrt{3/5})(0+\sqrt{3/5})}\, dx = \frac{8}{9}\\ c_{3}\amp = c_{1} =\frac{5}{9}\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <title><m>n=4</m></title>

      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle L_{4}(x) = \frac{35}{8}x^{4} -\frac{15}{4}x^{2} + \frac{3}{8}</m>. The roots are
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}\pm \sqrt{525 \pm 70 \sqrt{30}}/35 = \pm 0.8611363114, \pm 0.3399810437\end{aligned}
        </me>
        And the weights are:
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}c_{1}\amp =\int_{-1}^{1} \frac{(x-x_{2})(x-x_{3})(x-x_{4})}{(x_{1}-x_{2})(x_{1}-x_{3})(x_{1}-x_{4})}\, dx =\frac{-\sqrt{30}+18}{36}\approx 0.3478548451\\ c_{2}\amp =\int_{-1}^{1} \frac{(x-x_{1})(x-x_{3})(x-x_{4})}{(x_{2}-x_{1})(x_{1}-x_{3})(x_{1}-x_{4})}\, dx =\frac{\sqrt{30}+18}{36}\approx 0.6521451549\\ c_{3}\amp = c_{2} \\ c_{4}\amp = c_{1}\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <title><m>n=5</m></title>

      <p>
        <m>\displaystyle L_{5}(x) = \frac{63}{8}x^{5} - \frac{35}{4}x^{3} + \frac{15}{8}x</m>. The roots of this are:
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}0, \pm \frac{1}{3}\sqrt{5\pm \frac{2}{7} \sqrt{70}}\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        And the weights are:
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}c_{1}\amp =\int_{-1}^{1} \frac{(x-x_{2})(x-x_{3})(x-x_{4})(x-x_{5})}{(x_{1}-x_{2})(x_{1}-x_{3})(x_{1}-x_{4})(x_{1}-x_{5})}\, dx = \approx 0.23692688505618906\\ c_{2}\amp =\int_{-1}^{1} \frac{(x-x_{1})(x-x_{3})(x-x_{4})(x-x_{5})}{(x_{2}-x_{1})(x_{2}-x_{3})(x_{2}-x_{4})(x_{2}-x_{5})}\, dx = \approx 0.4786286704993666\\ c_{3}\amp = \int_{-1}^{1} \frac{(x-x_{1})(x-x_{2})(x-x_{4})(x-x_{5})}{(x_{3}-x_{1})(x_{3}-x_{2})(x_{3}-x_{4})(x_{3}-x_{5})}\, dx = \approx 0.5688888888888889\\ c_{4}\amp = c_{2} \\ c_{5}\amp = c_{1}\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <title><m>n=9</m></title>

      <p>
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}L_{9}(x)\amp ={\frac{12155}{128}}\,{x}^{9}-{\frac{6435}{32}}\,{x}^{7}+{\frac{9009 }{64}}\,{x}^{5}-{\frac{1155}{32}}\,{x}^{3}+{\frac{315}{128}}\,x\end{aligned}
        </me>
        and the roots are <m>\pm 0.9681602395, \pm 0.8360311073, \pm 0.6133714327, \pm 0.3242534234, 0.</m> And the weights are:
        <me>
          \begin{aligned}c_{9} = c_{1}\amp = 0.08127438847,\amp c_{8} = c_{2}\amp = .1806481604, \\ c_{7} = c_{3}\amp = 0.2606106962,\amp c_{6} =c_{4}\amp = 0.3123470765, \\ c_{5}\amp = 0.3302393555\end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>
    </dl>
  </p>

  <p>
    Use Gaussian Quadrature with 9 nodes to find
    <me>
      \begin{aligned}\int_{-1}^{1} e^{-x^2}\, dx\end{aligned}
    </me>
  </p>

  <p>
    <me>
      \begin{aligned}\sum_{k=1}^{9} c_{k} e^{-x_k^2}= 1.493648265645003840335173\end{aligned}
    </me>
    which is accurate to within <m>10^{-11}</m>.
  </p>
</section>